\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial herbs; stems erect, striate to ribbed, sometimes absent. Leaves in a basal rosette or alternate, usually deeply divided and with spiny segments. Capitula solitary or in a sparingly branched, corymbose cyme. Involucre ovoid to globose; involucral bracts imbricate, glabrous, the outer and middle with a stout spine or an ovate to triangular appendage at the apex. Receptacle fleshy, the scales setaceous. Florets all hermaphrodite. Corolla purplish, blue or white, tubular, 5-fid; style long-exserted. Achenes obpyramidal or obovoid-cylindrical, glabrous; pappus of many rows of plumose, dirty white hairs connate at the base.
