\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 5. C. cardunculus} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 827 (1753). Stems 20-100 cm, lanate. Leaves up to 50 × 35 cm, subcoriaceous, bright green and shortly tomentose above, white-tomentose beneath; segments ovate to linear-lanceolate, with rigid, yellow spines 15-35 mm at apex and clustered at base; lower leaves petiolate, the uppermost sessile. Involucre 45-60 × 40-55 mm, ovoid-globose; involucral bracts ovate to elliptical, gradually or abruptly narrowed into an erecto-patent spine 10-50 × 2-6 mm, glaucescent or purplish. Corolla blue, lilac or whitish. Achenes 6-8 × 3-4 mm, shiny, brown-spotted; pappus 25-40 mm. 2n = 34.{\i  Stony or waste places and dry grassland, mainly on clay soils. S. & W. parts of Mediterranean region and S. Portugal; occasionally cultivated elsewhere for the leaves which are blanched and eaten as a vegetable} ({\i cardoon}). Bl Co Cr Ga Gr Hs It Lu Sa Si.
